div.p:
1. Of the Church in generall. The common eſtate of Gods Church in this world, is to bee under the Croſſe, and the end of that is the Crowne of ioy and glory. A good iſſue there is of all the Saints trials: So in this Pſalme, the Jewiſh Church had been ſeventy yeares in the hard captivitie of Babylon: They hanged up their harpes at the willowes;
                  Pſal. 137.1, 2, 3.
                  they wept at the remembrance of Sion: their enemies flouted them, and required ſongs in their heavineſſe: too grievous to laſt alwayes, their God raiſeth up a Cyrus for them, who ſhall ſend them home to their own countrey, and not ſend them empty, but with great riches and encouragements: and, ſooner or later, the Church ſhall be rid of all tyrants and perſecuters, Antichriſt, Gog and Magog, and every enemy.
